ArchBang: About
===============

What is ArchBang?
-----------------

ArchBang is a lightweight, Arch Linux-based live ISO that combines the power and flexibility
of Arch with a modern, easy-to-use environment. It features labwc, a minimal Wayland
compositor, paired with essential tools and a cohesive visual theme for a smooth out-of-the-box
experience.


A Brief History
---------------

ArchBang's story begins not with Arch Linux, but with a love for CrunchBang — a Debian-based
live ISO built around the Openbox window manager, created by Philip Newborough. CrunchBang
offered something rare: a minimal, fast, beautifully consistent desktop that just worked,
without the weight of a full desktop environment. It built a devoted community of users who
valued simplicity above everything else.

The idea for ArchBang was born in a forum thread on the CrunchBang Forums, posted by Willensky
Aristide. His goal was straightforward — he wanted that same Openbox experience, but built on
a rolling release foundation. Arch Linux, with its lightweight and endlessly configurable base,
was the natural fit. With encouragement from the CrunchBang community the project took shape,
and the first release followed in January 2010.

By 2012, Stan McLaren had taken over as project leader. It was around this time that a forum
regular known as MrGreen began taking an increasingly active role in development — contributing,
building, and helping hold the community together. When Stan and another key contributor quietly
disappeared without fanfare or formal handover, MrGreen simply carried on. No announcement,
no ceremony — just someone who cared too much to let the project fade.

That quiet dedication has defined ArchBang ever since. Over the years the project evolved —
moving through different window managers, embracing systemd, and growing alongside the Arch
ecosystem. The most significant shift came with the move away from Openbox and tint2, both of
which had become less actively developed, to a Wayland-first approach built around labwc. It
was a natural progression: the broader Linux world was moving to Wayland, the major
distributions and compositors had made the switch, and MrGreen had been running Sway as his
daily driver for years. The direction was clear.

ArchBang today is still maintained by a single person in their spare time, with one ear always
open to the community. User feedback shapes the project as much as anything else.


Design Philosophy
-----------------

ArchBang is built around these core principles:

  * Lightweight - Minimal base system, fast installation, runs well on modest hardware
  * Beginner-friendly - Pre-configured, guided installer, clear documentation
  * Modern - Wayland-first approach with labwc instead of legacy Xorg
  * Flexible - Full Arch Linux under the hood for customization and package access
  * Coherent - Consistent theming (Catppuccin Mocha), thoughtful keybinds, unified experience


Why Wayland and labwc?
----------------------

Most beginner-friendly Linux distributions still use Xorg, a decades-old display server.
ArchBang takes a different approach: labwc is a minimal, modern Wayland compositor that
provides everything needed without the bloat or complexity of traditional desktop environments.

Benefits:
  - Simpler, more secure architecture
  - Better support for modern hardware (touchscreen, HiDPI displays)
  - Faster performance on limited resources
  - Native Wayland application support
  - No external dependencies for basic functionality


Target Audience
---------------

ArchBang is designed for:

  - Users new to Arch Linux who want a guided introduction
  - Those seeking a minimal, lightweight base system
  - Developers and system administrators who value simplicity and control
  - Users on older or modest hardware
  - Anyone interested in learning how to customize their Linux desktop


Features
--------

Installation
  - Menu-driven installer with clear steps
  - Support for UEFI and BIOS boot modes
  - Optional LVM and full-disk encryption (LUKS)
  - Automatic hardware detection (CPU, microcode)

Desktop Environment
  - labwc Wayland compositor
  - foot terminal (configured with scrollback and sensible defaults)
  - Catppuccin Mocha theme (dark, modern, easy on the eyes)
  - Custom keybinds for common tasks (volume, brightness, monitor, launcher)
  - Systemd for service management

Documentation
  - Comprehensive Guide for new users
  - Pre-configured examples and best practices
  - Links to Arch Wiki for deeper learning


How It's Maintained
-------------------

ArchBang is maintained by a single developer in their spare time. While this means updates
may be slower than larger projects, it also means every decision is thoughtful and the
project stays focused on its core mission: simplicity and ease of use.

If you find ArchBang useful and want to support its continued development:
Buy me a coffee: https://ko-fi.com/archbang


Getting Help
------------

ArchBang is not officially affiliated with Arch Linux. Questions specific to ArchBang or
how it differs from stock Arch should be asked in ArchBang communities, not the Arch forums.

For Arch-related questions, check the Arch Wiki:
https://wiki.archlinux.org

For more information about ArchBang, visit:
https://archbang.org/

